Part I - Prosper Loan Data¶

By: Joseph Tanner¶

Introduction¶

The data set I will be exploring and then explaining is the Prosper Loan Data set. This data set contains 81 columns and 113937 rows. This data contains multiple different aspects of loan details. We will be using this loan data to break down inter-connections and make visualizations that tell a story for the data.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

def plotFunction(plt, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    #Here we are going to set up a function to help eliminate repeated functions.
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt. ylabel

Conclusions¶

Through out this data analysis, we explored the multiple variables in prosper loans. The columns we utilized for our analysis were 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'CreditScore', 'BorrowerAPR', 'StatedMonthlyIncome', 'Term', 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', and 'EmploymentStatus'. While overviewing and ploting data for relationships we found the bigest factors on APR were CreitScore(negative correlation), ProsperRating (Alpha)(Negative COrrelation), and Term length(Negative Correlation). Credit Score had the highest correlation of -.43. With these negative correlations the higher your term length, the higher your Prosperrating, and the higher your credit score the lower your APR would be on average.
